    {
      "id": "flow-notes",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 14.08553552905687,
      "y": 870,
      "width": 1446.0333481302393,
      "height": 307.69329944017994,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 5070,
      "version": 117,
      "versionNonce": 2030122198,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1779956830298,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Cloudsoft.Web is the browser-facing MVC app. Requests enter controllers, then move into Cloudsoft.Core services through dependency-injected\ninterfaces.\n2. Cloudsoft.Api exposes HTTP endpoints under /api/jobs. It uses DTOs to shape API input/output and maps DTOs to Core models.\n3. Cloudsoft.Core holds the domain models, service classes, repository interfaces, repository implementations, options, and storage abstractions used by\nboth Web and API.\n4. Services contain business flow decisions: create jobs, submit applications, authenticate employers, validate countries, and coordinate persistence.\n5. Repositories isolate persistence. Tests and local development can use in-memory repositories; Azure configuration can use MongoDB-backed resilient\nrepositories.\n6. Unit tests call controllers, services, repositories, and validators directly. They are fast and focus on one class or behavior at a time.\n7. Integration tests use WebApplicationFactory to start Cloudsoft.Web or Cloudsoft.Api in memory, send real HTTP requests, handle antiforgery tokens,\nand verify end-to-end user stories.\n8. EnvironmentVariableScope and test factories keep test configuration isolated, including Development environment and feature-flag settings, so tests\ndo not depend on the developer machine state.",
      "originalText": "1. Cloudsoft.Web is the browser-facing MVC app. Requests enter controllers, then move into Cloudsoft.Core services through dependency-injected interfaces.\n2. Cloudsoft.Api exposes HTTP endpoints under /api/jobs. It uses DTOs to shape API input/output and maps DTOs to Core models.\n3. Cloudsoft.Core holds the domain models, service classes, repository interfaces, repository implementations, options, and storage abstractions used by both Web and API.\n4. Services contain business flow decisions: create jobs, submit applications, authenticate employers, validate countries, and coordinate persistence.\n5. Repositories isolate persistence. Tests and local development can use in-memory repositories; Azure configuration can use MongoDB-backed resilient repositories.\n6. Unit tests call controllers, services, repositories, and validators directly. They are fast and focus on one class or behavior at a time.\n7. Integration tests use WebApplicationFactory to start Cloudsoft.Web or Cloudsoft.Api in memory, send real HTTP requests, handle antiforgery tokens, and verify end-to-end user stories.\n8. EnvironmentVariableScope and test factories keep test configuration isolated, including Development environment and feature-flag settings, so tests do not depend on the developer machine state.",
      "fontSize": 18.934972273241844,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "lineHeight": 1.25,
      "index": "aZ",
      "autoResize": false
    }
  ],
